ce:section.ce:para:
The transport process of Li+ includes diffusion and electric migration [25]. The relevant transport parameters include electric conductivity (
                              σ
                           ), diffusion coefficient (
                              D
                           ), and transference number (
                              t
                           ). Unfortunately, there is a lack of electrochemical experiments that have investigated the diffusion coefficient and transference number of electrolytes in LIBs [26]. This scarcity of research is primarily due to the difficulty of accurately extracting the transport characteristics of Li+ solely from the electrical responses from batteries. The diffusion coefficient of ions can be accurately measured using the pulsed field gradient nuclear magnetic resonance (PFG-NMR) technique, which can measure the self-diffusion process directly [27–29]. On the other hand, the determination of Li+ transference numbers is often performed under direct current polarization [26,27]. The accuracy of this method is still questionable due to the presence of side reactions, the formation of ion pairs, and a weak assumption of a diluted solution condition [30].
